# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: applied-mechanics-reviews
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/applied-mechanics-reviews] The journal is abstracted and indexed in Science Citation Index, Current Contents/Engineering, Computing & Technology, Chemical Abstracts Service, and Scopus.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/applied-mechanics-reviews] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2020 impact factor of 7.281.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] The two principal databases that support the different products are CAplus and Registry.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] CAS References consists of bibliographic information and abstracts for all articles in chemical journals worldwide, and chemistry-related articles from all scientific journals, patents, and other scientific publications.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] As of 2023, the CAS Registry contains information on more than 200 million organic and inorganic substances, and about 70 million protein and nucleic acid sequences.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] The sequence information comes from CAS and GenBank, produced by the National Institutes of Health.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] The chemical information is produced by CAS, and is prepared by the CAS Registry System, which identifies each compound with a specific CAS registry number, index name, and graphic representation of its chemical structure.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] The assignment of chemical names is done according to the chemical nomenclature rules for *CA* index names, which is slightly different from the internationally standard IUPAC names, according to the rules of IUPAC.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] CAS databases are available via two principal database systems, STN, and SciFinder.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] STN (Scientific & Technical Information Network) International is operated jointly by CAS and FIZ Karlsruhe, and is intended primarily for information professionals, using a command language interface.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] In addition to CAS databases, STN also provides access to many other databases, similar to Dialog.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] SciFinder is a database of chemical and bibliographic information.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] Originally it was available only as a client application (for both Windows and MacOS operating systems), a web version was released in 2008.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] By that time it had a graphical interface, and was able to do graphical searches for chemical structures and reactions (the first database to allow such functions), as well as keyword searches for literature in chemistry and related disciplines.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] SciFinder Scholar was a very similar a product developed for academic institutions, but discontinued in 2023.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] In 2017 the ACS released SciFinder-n as a web-only product with the same data content and improved user interface and search functions.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] SciFinder is considered as the best source of chemical information worldwide, with substantially larger number of relevant information sources than Web of Science or Scopus with Reaxys.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] However, due to its unique and unusual search functions, substantial training is needed in order to fully take advantage of SciFinder capabilities.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] The range is from 1907 to the present, including both serial and non-serial scientific and technical publications.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] *Beyond CASSI* lists abbreviated journal titles from early chemical literature and other historical reference sources.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] For many years, beginning in 1909, the offices of *Chemical Abstracts* were housed in various places on the Columbus, Ohio campus of Ohio State University, including McPherson Laboratory and Watts Hall.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] In 1965, CAS moved to a new 50-acre (200,000 m2) site on the west bank of the Olentangy River, just north of The Ohio State campus.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] This campus became well known in the Columbus area and famous as the site of many Columbus Symphony Orchestra pop concerts.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] In 2009, the campus consisted of three buildings.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] Noyes had enlarged the *Review of American Chemical Research*, an abstracting publication begun by Arthur Noyes in 1895 that was the forerunner of *Chemical Abstracts*.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] When it became evident that a separate publication containing these abstracts was needed, Noyes became the first editor of the new publication, *Chemical Abstracts*.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] Crane became the first Director of Chemical Abstracts Service when it became an American Chemical Society division in 1956.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] Crane had been *CA* editor since 1915, and his dedication was a key factor in its long-term success.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] Baker became the CAS Director upon Crane's retirement in 1958.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] According to CAS, his visionary view of CAS' potential "led to expansion, modernization, and the forging of international alliances with other information organizations." CAS was an early leader in the use of computer technology to organize and disseminate information.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] The CAS Chemical Registry System was introduced in 1965.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] CAS developed a unique registry number to identify chemical substances.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] Environmental Protection Agency and local fire departments around the world now rely on these numbers for the definite identification of substances.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] According to the ACS, this is the largest chemical substance database in the world.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] In 1965, CAS left their offices at OSU for a new headquarters north of campus.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] Ground was broken in 1971 for an expansion to the building designed by architects Brubaker/Brandt to accommodate the review of 400,000 new research reports printed each year.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] The 5-story 142,000 square foot building opened in May 1973.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] In 2007, the ACS designated its Chemical Abstracts Service subdivision an ACS National Historic Chemical Landmark in recognition of its significance as a comprehensive repository of research in chemistry and related sciences.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] In 2021, CAS rebranded along with a change in logo.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] The organization updated their mission to be more focused on dynamic responsiveness due to ongoing changes within scientific industries and communities.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/chemical-abstracts-service] In 2022, CAS announced the release of almost half a million CAS registry numbers under an open license in their Common Chemistry project.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] Clarivate formed in 2016, following the acquisition of Thomson Reuters' Intellectual Property and Science business by Onex Corporation and Baring Private Equity Asia.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] Since 2016, Clarivate acquired various companies, notably ProQuest in 2021.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] On July 11, 2016, Thomson Reuters a $3.55 billion sale of its Intellectual Property and Science business to private equity firms Onex Corporation and Baring Private Equity Asia.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] The transaction was completed on October 4, 2016, and Clarivate Analytics became an independent company as a corporate spin-off.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] In May 2019, Clarivate merged with the Churchill Capital Corp SPAC to obtain a public listing on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE), trading under symbol CLVT.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] On March 11, 2022, Clarivate, which has an office in Odesa, Ukraine, announced it would cease all commercial activity in Russia following Russia's full-scale invasion of Ukraine on February 22, 2022.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] As of 2023, Clarivate conducts operations through three strategic business units: Intellectual Property Group, Life Sciences & Healthcare Group, and Academic and Government Group, each led by a president.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] On July 11, 2022, Clarivate announced Jerre Stead's retirement and transition from Executive Chair and CEO to Non-Executive Chair.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] IHS Markit CFO Jonathan Gear joined Clarivate as CEO-elect on July 11, 2022, becoming CEO on September 1, 2022.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] On September 1, 2022, Clarivate announced Jerre Stead's retirement from the Board and appointment as Chair Emeritus effective October 20, 2022.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] On August 6, 2024, Clarivate appointed former ProQuest CEO Matti Shem Tov as CEO.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] As Clarivate acquired ProQuest, various products of ProQuest are being operated under Clarivate, which encompasses products that ProQuest had taken on relatively recently, through acquisitions of its own—notably those of Innovative Interfaces: Vega, Sierra, Polaris, Millennium, and Virtua.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] The Derwent World Patents Index (DWPI) is a database containing patent applications and grants from 44 of the world's patent issuing authorities.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] ScholarOne is a submission management system to allow an editor of an academic journal to manage electronic submission of authors' manuscripts for publication, to recruit reviewers of those manuscripts, to check authors' compliance with the journal's requirements, and to communicate with authors.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] It was sold to the American software company Silverchair in 2024.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] Clarivate publishes an annual Highly Cited Researchers list.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] The 2019 list of Highly Cited Researchers was released on November 19, 2019.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] Clarivate Citation Laureates, formerly Thomson Reuters Citation Laureates, is a list of candidates considered likely to win the Nobel Prize in their respective field.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] The candidates are so named based on the citation impact of their published research.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] Thomson Reuters Citation Laureates was established in 1989.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] The list pertains to likely Nobel Prize winners in medicine, chemistry, physics, and economics.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] There appears to be a correlation between high citation rates for a published researcher and the award of prestigious accolades.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] Furthermore, citation rates disclose researchers furnishing instrumental contributions that advance the science of their respective field.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] Finally, choosing one tenth of one percent (0.1%) of the highest impact papers winnows the analysis to the topics and people most likely to be selected by Nobel selection committee.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] From 2002 to 2020, 59 individuals listed as Citation Laureates have received Nobel prizes.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] The annual Top 100 Global Innovators report identifies the world's most innovative organizations.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] These businesses have successfully developed valuable patented inventions that also have strong commercialization potential based on market reach and impact on other downstream inventions.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/clarivate-analytics] The 2020 Top 100 Global Innovators Report was released on February 19, 2020.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/current-contents] Still published in print, it is available as one of the databases included in Clarivate Analytics' Web of Science with daily updates, and also through other database aggregators.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/editor-in-chief] An **editor-in-chief** (**EIC**), also known as **lead editor**, **chief editor**, **executive editor**, or simply **editor** is a publication's editorial leader who has final responsibility for its operations and policies.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/editor-in-chief] The editor-in-chief heads all departments of the organization and is held accountable for delegating tasks to staff members and managing them.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/editor-in-chief] The term is often used at newspapers, magazines, yearbooks, and television news programs.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/editor-in-chief] The editor-in-chief is commonly the link between the publisher or proprietor and the editorial staff.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/editor-in-chief] The term is also applied to academic journals, where the editor-in-chief gives the ultimate decision whether a submitted manuscript will be published.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/editor-in-chief] This decision is made by the editor-in-chief after seeking input from reviewers selected on the basis of relevant expertise.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/editor-in-chief] For larger journals, the decision is often upon the recommendation of one of several associate editors who each have responsibility for a fraction of the submitted manuscripts.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The traditional disciplines of engineering are civil, mechanical, electrical, and chemical.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The academic discipline of engineering encompasses a broad range of more specialized subfields, and each can have a more specific emphasis for applications of mathematics and science.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Modern engineering practice follows the engineering design process and spans multiple fields, which include designing and improving infrastructure, machinery, vehicles, electronics, materials, and energy systems.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] As a human endeavor, engineering has existed since ancient times, starting with the six classic simple machines.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Examples of large-scale engineering projects from antiquity include impressive structures like the pyramids, elegant temples such as the Parthenon, and water conveyances like hulled watercraft, canals, and the Roman aqueduct.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Early machines were powered by humans and animals, then later by wind.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Machines of war were invented for siegecraft.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In Europe, the scientific and industrial revolutions advanced engineering into a scientific profession and resulted in continuing technological improvements.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The steam engine provided much greater power than animals, leading to mechanical propulsion for ships and railways.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Further scientific advances resulted in the application of engineering to electrical, chemical, and aerospace requirements, plus the use of new materials for greater efficiencies.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The word *engineering* is derived from the Latin *ingenium*.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineers typically follow a code of ethics that favors honesty and integrity, while being dedicated to public safety and welfare.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineering tasks involve finding optimal solutions to constrained problems, with testing and simulations being used prior to production.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] When a deployed product fails, forensic engineering is used to determine what went wrong in order to find a fix.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Much of this product lifecycle management is now assisted with computer software, from design to testing and manufacturing.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] At larger scales, this process is normally funded by a company, multiple investors, or the government, so a knowledge of economics and business practices is needed.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineering has existed since ancient times, when humans devised inventions such as the wedge, lever, wheel and pulley, etc.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The term *engineering* is derived from the word *engineer*, which itself dates back to the 14th century when an *engine'er* (literally, one who builds or operates a *siege engine*) referred to "a constructor of military engines".
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In this context, now obsolete, an "engine" referred to a military machine, *i.e.*, a mechanical contraption used in war (for example, a catapult).
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Notable examples of the obsolete usage which have survived to the present day are military engineering corps, *e.g.*, the U.S.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The word "engine" itself is of even older origin, ultimately deriving from the Latin *ingenium* (c.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Other monuments, no longer standing, such as the Hanging Gardens of Babylon and the Pharos of Alexandria, were important engineering achievements of their time and were considered among the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The six classic simple machines were known in the ancient Near East.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The wedge and the inclined plane (ramp) were known since prehistoric times.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The wheel, along with the wheel and axle mechanism, was invented in Mesopotamia (modern Iraq) during the 5th millennium BC.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The lever mechanism first appeared around 5,000 years ago in the Near East, where it was used in a simple balance scale, and to move large objects in Egyptian technology.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The lever was also used in the shadoof water-lifting device, the first crane machine, which appeared in Mesopotamia c.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] 3000 BC, and then in Egyptian technology c.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The earliest evidence of pulleys date back to Mesopotamia in the early 2nd millennium BC, and ancient Egypt during the Twelfth Dynasty (1991–1802 BC).
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The screw, the last of the simple machines to be invented, first appeared in Mesopotamia during the Neo-Assyrian period (911–609) BC.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The Egyptian pyramids were built using three of the six simple machines, the inclined plane, the wedge, and the lever, to create structures like the Great Pyramid of Giza.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The earliest civil engineer known by name is Imhotep.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] As one of the officials of the Pharaoh, Djosèr, he probably designed and supervised the construction of the Pyramid of Djoser (the Step Pyramid) at Saqqara in Egypt around 2630–2611 BC.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The earliest practical water-powered machines, the water wheel and watermill, first appeared in the Persian Empire, in what are now Iraq and Iran, by the early 4th century BC.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Kush developed the Sakia during the 4th century BC, which relied on animal power instead of human energy.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Hafirs were developed as a type of reservoir in Kush to store and contain water as well as boost irrigation.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Kushite ancestors built speos during the Bronze Age between 3700 and 3250 BC.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Bloomeries and blast furnaces were also created during the 7th centuries BC in Kush.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Wooden plank-built seafaring ships were being engineered and built during the Bronze Age, as evidenced by the Uluburun shipwreck, dated from around 1300 BCE.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Ancient Greece developed machines in both civilian and military domains, as evidenced by the writings of Philo of Byzantium and others.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The Antikythera mechanism, an early known mechanical analog computer, and the mechanical inventions of Archimedes, are examples of Greek mechanical engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Ancient Chinese, Greek, Roman and Hunnic armies employed military machines and inventions such as artillery which was developed by the Greeks around the 4th century BC, the trireme, the ballista and the catapult, the trebuchet by Chinese circa 6th-5th century BCE.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The earliest practical wind-powered machines, the windmill and wind pump, first appeared in the Muslim world during the Islamic Golden Age, in what are now Iran, Afghanistan, and Pakistan, by the 9th century AD.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The earliest practical steam-powered machine was a steam jack driven by a steam turbine, described in 1551 by Taqi al-Din Muhammad ibn Ma'ruf in Ottoman Egypt.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The cotton gin was invented in India by the 6th century AD, and the spinning wheel was invented in the Islamic world by the early 11th century, both of which were fundamental to the growth of the cotton industry.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The spinning wheel was also a precursor to the spinning jenny, which was a key development during the early Industrial Revolution in the 18th century.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The earliest programmable machines were developed in the Muslim world.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] A music sequencer, a programmable musical instrument, was the earliest type of programmable machine.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The first music sequencer was an automated flute player invented by the Banu Musa brothers, described in their *Book of Ingenious Devices*, in the 9th century.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In 1206, Al-Jazari invented programmable automata/robots.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] He described four automaton musicians, including drummers operated by a programmable drum machine, where they could be made to play different rhythms and different drum patterns.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Before the development of modern engineering, mathematics was used by artisans and craftsmen, such as millwrights, clockmakers, instrument makers and surveyors.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Aside from these professions, universities were not believed to have had much practical significance to technology.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] A standard reference for the state of mechanical arts during the Renaissance is given in the mining engineering treatise *De re metallica* (1556), which also contains sections on geology, mining, and chemistry.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] *De re metallica* was the standard chemistry reference for the next 180 years.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The science of classical mechanics, sometimes called Newtonian mechanics, formed the scientific basis of much of modern engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] With the rise of engineering as a profession in the 18th century, the term became more narrowly applied to fields in which mathematics and science were applied to these ends.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Similarly, in addition to military and civil engineering, the fields then known as the mechanic arts became incorporated into engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Canal building was an important engineering work during the early phases of the Industrial Revolution.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] John Smeaton was the first self-proclaimed civil engineer and is often regarded as the "father" of civil engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] He was an English civil engineer responsible for the design of bridges, canals, harbors, and lighthouses.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] He was also a capable mechanical engineer and an eminent physicist.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Using a model water wheel, Smeaton conducted experiments for seven years, determining ways to increase efficiency.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Smeaton introduced iron axles and gears to water wheels.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Smeaton also made mechanical improvements to the Newcomen steam engine.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Smeaton designed the third Eddystone Lighthouse (1755–59) where he pioneered the use of 'hydraulic lime' (a form of mortar which will set under water) and developed a technique involving dovetailed blocks of granite in the building of the lighthouse.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] He is important in the history, rediscovery of, and development of modern cement, because he identified the compositional requirements needed to obtain "hydraulicity" in lime; work which led ultimately to the invention of Portland cement.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Applied science led to the development of the steam engine.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Edward Somerset, 2nd Marquess of Worcester published a book of 100 inventions containing a method for raising waters similar to a coffee percolator.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Samuel Morland, a mathematician and inventor who worked on pumps, left notes at the Vauxhall Ordinance Office on a steam pump design that Thomas Savery read.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In 1698 Savery built a steam pump called "The Miner's Friend".
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Iron merchant Thomas Newcomen, who built the first commercial piston steam engine in 1712, was not known to have any scientific training.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The application of steam-powered cast iron blowing cylinders for providing pressurized air for blast furnaces lead to a large increase in iron production in the late 18th century.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The higher furnace temperatures made possible with steam-powered blast allowed for the use of more lime in blast furnaces, which enabled the transition from charcoal to coke.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] These innovations lowered the cost of iron, making horse railways and iron bridges practical.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The puddling process, patented by Henry Cort in 1784 produced large scale quantities of wrought iron.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Hot blast, patented by James Beaumont Neilson in 1828, greatly lowered the amount of fuel needed to smelt iron.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] With the development of the high pressure steam engine, the power to weight ratio of steam engines made practical steamboats and locomotives possible.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] New steel making processes, such as the Bessemer process and the open hearth furnace, ushered in an area of heavy engineering in the late 19th century.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] One of the most famous engineers of the mid-19th century was Isambard Kingdom Brunel, who built railroads, dockyards and steamships.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The Industrial Revolution created a demand for machinery with metal parts, which led to the development of several machine tools.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Boring cast iron cylinders with precision was not possible until John Wilkinson invented his boring machine, which is considered the first machine tool.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Other machine tools included the screw cutting lathe, milling machine, turret lathe and the metal planer.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Precision machining techniques were developed in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] These included the use of gigs to guide the machining tool over the work and fixtures to hold the work in the proper position.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Machine tools and machining techniques capable of producing interchangeable parts lead to large scale factory production by the late 19th century.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The United States Census of 1850 listed the occupation of "engineer" for the first time with a count of 2,000.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] There were fewer than 50 engineering graduates in the U.S. before 1865.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The first PhD in engineering (technically, *applied science and engineering*) awarded in the United States went to Josiah Willard Gibbs at Yale University in 1863; it was also the second PhD awarded in science in the U.S.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In 1870 there were a dozen U.S. mechanical engineering graduates, with that number increasing to 43 per year in 1875.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In 1890, there were 6,000 engineers in civil, mining, mechanical and electrical.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] There was no chair of applied mechanism and applied mechanics at Cambridge until 1875, and no chair of engineering at Oxford until 1907.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Germany established technical universities earlier.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The foundations of electrical engineering in the 1800s included the experiments of Alessandro Volta, Michael Faraday, Georg Ohm and others and the invention of the electric telegraph in 1816 and the electric motor in 1872.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The theoretical work of James Maxwell (see: Maxwell's equations) and Heinrich Hertz in the late 19th century gave rise to the field of electronics.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The later inventions of the vacuum tube and the transistor further accelerated the development of electronics to such an extent that electrical and electronics engineers currently outnumber their colleagues of any other engineering specialty.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Chemical engineering developed in the late nineteenth century.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Industrial scale manufacturing demanded new materials and new processes and by 1880 the need for large scale production of chemicals was such that a new industry was created, dedicated to the development and large scale manufacturing of chemicals in new industrial plants.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The role of the chemical engineer was the design of these chemical plants and processes.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Originally deriving from the manufacture of ceramics and its putative derivative metallurgy, materials science is one of the oldest forms of engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Modern materials science evolved directly from metallurgy, which itself evolved from the use of fire.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Important elements of modern materials science were products of the Space Race; the understanding and engineering of the metallic alloys, and silica and carbon materials, used in building space vehicles enabling the exploration of space.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Materials science has driven, and been driven by, the development of revolutionary technologies such as rubbers, plastics, semiconductors, and biomaterials.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Aeronautical engineering deals with aircraft design process design while aerospace engineering is a more modern term that expands the reach of the discipline by including spacecraft design.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Its origins can be traced back to the aviation pioneers around the start of the 20th century although the work of Sir George Cayley has recently been dated as being from the last decade of the 18th century.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Early knowledge of aeronautical engineering was largely empirical with some concepts and skills imported from other branches of engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Only a decade after the successful flights by the Wright brothers, there was extensive development of aeronautical engineering through development of military aircraft that were used in World War I.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Meanwhile, research to provide fundamental background science continued by combining theoretical physics with experiments.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineering is a broad discipline that is often broken down into several sub-disciplines.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Although most engineers will usually be trained in a specific discipline, some engineers become multi-disciplined through experience.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Below is a list of recognized branches of engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Note that there are additional sub-disciplines.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Interdisciplinary engineering draws from more than one of the principle branches of the practice.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Historically, naval engineering and mining engineering were major branches.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Other engineering fields are manufacturing engineering, acoustical engineering, corrosion engineering, instrumentation and control, automotive, information engineering, petroleum, systems, audio, software, architectural, biosystems, and textile engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] These and other branches of engineering are represented in the 40 licensed member institutions of the UK Engineering Council, as of 2025.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] New specialties sometimes combine with the traditional fields and form new branches – for example, Earth systems engineering and management involves a wide range of subject areas including engineering studies, environmental science, engineering ethics and philosophy of engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] One who practices engineering is called an engineer, and those licensed to do so may have more formal designations such as Professional Engineer, Chartered Engineer, Incorporated Engineer, Ingenieur, European Engineer.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] There can also be what is called by the FAA a Designated Engineering Representative.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In the engineering design process, engineers apply mathematics and the physical sciences to find novel solutions to problems or to improve existing solutions.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineers need proficient knowledge of relevant sciences for their design projects.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] As a result, many engineers continue to learn new material throughout their careers.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] If multiple solutions exist, engineers weigh each design choice based on their merit and choose the solution that best matches the requirements.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The task of the engineer is to identify, understand, and interpret the constraints on a design in order to yield a successful result.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] It is generally insufficient to build a technically successful product, rather, it must also meet further requirements.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Constraints may include the fundamental laws of physics and chemistry, available resources, physical, imaginative or technical limitations, flexibility for future modifications and additions, and other factors, such as requirements for cost, safety, marketability, productivity, and serviceability.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] By understanding the constraints, engineers derive specifications for the limits within which a viable object or system may be produced and operated.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineers use their knowledge of science, mathematics, logic, economics, and appropriate experience or tacit knowledge to find suitable solutions to a particular problem.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Creating an appropriate mathematical model of a problem often allows them to analyze it (sometimes definitively), and to test potential solutions.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] More than one solution to a design problem usually exists so the different design choices have to be evaluated on their merits before the one judged most suitable is chosen.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Genrich Altshuller, after gathering statistics on a large number of patents, suggested that compromises are at the heart of "low-level" engineering designs, while at a higher level the best design is one which eliminates the core contradiction causing the problem.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineers typically attempt to predict how well their designs will perform to their specifications prior to full-scale production.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] They use, among other things: prototypes, scale models, simulations, destructive tests, nondestructive tests, and stress tests.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Testing ensures that products will perform as expected but only in so far as the testing has been representative of use in service.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] For products, such as aircraft, that are used differently by different users failures and unexpected shortcomings (and necessary design changes) can be expected throughout the operational life of the product.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineers take on the responsibility of producing designs that will perform as well as expected and, except those employed in specific areas of the arms industry, will not harm people.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineers typically include a factor of safety in their designs to reduce the risk of unexpected failure.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] This philosophy is embodied by Cicero's Creed, now considered the original engineer's code of ethics.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The study of failed products is known as forensic engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] It attempts to identify the cause of failure to allow a redesign of the product and so prevent a re-occurrence.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Careful analysis is needed to establish the cause of failure of a product.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The consequences of a failure may vary in severity from the minor cost of a machine breakdown to large loss of life in the case of accidents involving aircraft and large stationary structures like buildings and dams.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] These larger scale engineering disasters can arise from shortcuts or errors in the design process, such as miscalculations and miscommunication.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] They can also happen as a result of fatigue failure due to stress, temperature, or corrosion.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Faulty computer software can also play a role.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] As with all modern scientific and technological endeavors, computers and software play an increasingly important role.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] As well as the typical business application software there are a number of computer aided applications (computer-aided technologies) specifically for engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Computers can be used to generate models of fundamental physical processes, which can be solved using numerical methods.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] One of the most widely used design tools in the profession is computer-aided design (CAD) software.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] It enables engineers to create 3D models, 2D drawings, and schematics of their designs.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] CAD together with digital mockup (DMU) and CAE software such as finite element method analysis or analytic element method allows engineers to create models of designs that can be analyzed without having to make expensive and time-consuming physical prototypes.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Access and distribution of all this information is generally organized with the use of product data management software.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In recent years the use of computer software to aid the development of goods has collectively come to be known as product lifecycle management (PLM).
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The engineering profession engages in a range of activities, from collaboration at the societal level, and smaller individual projects.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Almost all engineering projects are obligated to a funding source: a company, a set of investors, or a government.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The types of engineering that are less constrained by such a funding source, are *pro bono*, and open-design engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineering has interconnections with society, culture, and human behavior.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Most products and constructions used by modern society, are influenced by engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineering activities have an impact on the environment, society, economies, and public safety.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineering projects can be controversial.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Examples from different engineering disciplines include: the development of nuclear weapons, the Three Gorges Dam, the design and use of sport utility vehicles, and the extraction of oil.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In response, some engineering companies have enacted serious corporate and social responsibility policies.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The attainment of many of the Millennium Development Goals requires the achievement of sufficient engineering capacity to develop infrastructure and sustainable technological development.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Overseas development and relief NGOs make considerable use of engineers, to apply solutions in disaster and development scenarios.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineering companies in more developed economies face challenges with regard to the number of engineers being trained, compared with those retiring.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] This problem is prominent in the UK where engineering has a poor image and low status.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] There are negative economic and political issues that this can cause, as well as ethical issues.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] It is agreed the engineering profession faces an "image crisis".
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The UK holds the most engineering companies compared to other European countries, together with the United States.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Many engineering societies have established codes of practice and codes of ethics to guide members and inform the public at large.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In Canada, engineers wear the Iron Ring as a symbol and reminder of the obligations and ethics associated with their profession.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] There exists an overlap between the sciences and engineering practice; in engineering, one applies science.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Both areas of endeavor rely on accurate observation of materials and phenomena.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Both use mathematics and classification criteria to analyze and communicate observations.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Scientists may also have to complete engineering tasks, such as designing experimental apparatus or building prototypes.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Conversely, in the process of developing technology, engineers sometimes find themselves exploring new phenomena, thus becoming, for the moment, scientists or more precisely "engineering scientists".
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In the book *What Engineers Know and How They Know It*, Walter Vincenti asserts that engineering research has a character different from that of scientific research.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] First, it often deals with areas in which the basic physics or chemistry are well understood, but the problems themselves are too complex to solve in an exact manner.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] There is a "real and important" difference between engineering and physics as similar to any science field has to do with technology.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Physics is an exploratory science that seeks knowledge of principles while engineering uses knowledge for practical applications of principles.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The former equates an understanding into a mathematical principle while the latter measures variables involved and creates technology.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] For technology, physics is an auxiliary and in a way technology is considered as applied physics.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Though physics and engineering are interrelated, it does not mean that a physicist is trained to do an engineer's job.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] A physicist would typically require additional and relevant training.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Physicists and engineers engage in different lines of work.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] But PhD physicists who specialize in sectors of engineering physics and applied physics are titled as Technology officer, R&D Engineers and System Engineers.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] An example of this is the use of numerical approximations to the Navier–Stokes equations to describe aerodynamic flow over an aircraft, or the use of the finite element method to calculate the stresses in complex components.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Second, engineering research employs many semi-empirical methods that are foreign to pure scientific research, one example being the method of parameter variation.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The study of the human body, albeit from different directions and for different purposes, is an important common link between medicine and some engineering disciplines.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Medicine aims to sustain, repair, enhance and even replace functions of the human body, if necessary, through the use of technology.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Modern medicine can replace several of the body's functions through the use of artificial organs and can significantly alter the function of the human body through artificial devices such as, for example, brain implants and pacemakers.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The fields of bionics and medical bionics are dedicated to the study of synthetic implants pertaining to natural systems.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Conversely, some engineering disciplines view the human body as a biological machine worth studying and are dedicated to emulating many of its functions by replacing biology with technology.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] This has led to fields such as artificial intelligence, neural networks, fuzzy logic, and robotics.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] There are also substantial interdisciplinary interactions between engineering and medicine.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Both fields provide solutions to real world problems.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] This often requires moving forward before phenomena are completely understood in a more rigorous scientific sense and therefore experimentation and empirical knowledge is an integral part of both.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Medicine, in part, studies the function of the human body.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The human body, as a biological machine, has many functions that can be modeled using engineering methods.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The heart for example functions much like a pump, the skeleton is like a linked structure with levers, the brain produces electrical signals etc.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] These similarities as well as the increasing importance and application of engineering principles in medicine, led to the development of the field of biomedical engineering that uses concepts developed in both disciplines.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Newly emerging branches of science, such as systems biology, are adapting analytical tools traditionally used for engineering, such as systems modeling and computational analysis, to the description of biological systems.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] There are connections between engineering and art, for example, architecture, landscape architecture and industrial design (even to the extent that these disciplines may sometimes be included in a university's Faculty of Engineering).
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The Art Institute of Chicago, for instance, held an exhibition about the art of NASA's aerospace design.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Robert Maillart's bridge design is perceived by some to have been deliberately artistic.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] At the University of South Florida, an engineering professor, through a grant with the National Science Foundation, has developed a course that connects art and engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Among famous historical figures, Leonardo da Vinci is a well-known Renaissance artist and engineer, and a prime example of the nexus between art and engineering.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Business engineering deals with the relationship between professional engineering, IT systems, business administration and change management.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineering management or "Management engineering" is a specialized field of management concerned with engineering practice or the engineering industry sector.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] The demand for management-focused engineers (or from the opposite perspective, managers with an understanding of engineering), has resulted in the development of specialized engineering management degrees that develop the knowledge and skills needed for these roles.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] During an engineering management course, students will develop industrial engineering skills, knowledge, and expertise, alongside knowledge of business administration, management techniques, and strategic thinking.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Engineers specializing in change management must have in-depth knowledge of the application of industrial and organizational psychology principles and methods.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Professional engineers often train as certified management consultants in the very specialized field of management consulting applied to engineering practice or the engineering sector.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] This combination of technical engineering practice, management consulting practice, industry sector knowledge, and change management expertise enables professional engineers who are also qualified as management consultants to lead major business transformation initiatives.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] These initiatives are typically sponsored by C-level executives.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] In political science, the term *engineering* has been borrowed for the study of the subjects of social engineering and political engineering, which deal with forming political and social structures using engineering methodology coupled with political science principles.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/engineering] Marketing engineering and financial engineering have similarly borrowed the term.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The **impact factor** (**IF**) or **journal impact factor** (**JIF**) of an academic journal is a type of journal ranking.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Journals with higher impact-factor values are considered more prestigious or important within their field.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Impact factor is a scientometric index calculated by Clarivate's Web of Science.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The impact factor of a journal reflects the yearly mean number of article citations published in the last two years.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] While frequently used by universities and funding bodies to decide on promotion and research proposals, it has been criticised for distorting good scientific practices.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The impact factor was devised by Eugene Garfield, the founder of the Institute for Scientific Information (ISI) in Philadelphia.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Impact factors began to be calculated yearly starting from 1975 for journals listed in the *Journal Citation Reports* (JCR).
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] ISI was acquired by Thomson Scientific & Healthcare in 1992, and became known as Thomson ISI.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] In 2018, Thomson-Reuters spun off and sold ISI to Onex Corporation and Baring Private Equity Asia.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] They founded a new corporation, Clarivate, which continued publishing the JCR.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] This means that, on average, its papers published in 2015 and 2016 received roughly 42 citations each in 2017.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Impact factors are reported in the subsequent year, when all of the previous year's publications have been processed by the indexing agency.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The value of impact factor depends on how to define "citations" and "publications"; the latter are often referred to as "citable items".
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] WoS is accessible to all registered users, who can independently verify the number of citable items for a given journal.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] In contrast, the number of citations is extracted not from the WoS database, but from a dedicated JCR database, which is not accessible to general readers.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Hence, the commonly used "JCR Impact Factor" is a proprietary value, which is defined and calculated by ISI and can not be verified by external users.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] New journals, which are indexed from their first published issue, will receive an impact factor after two years of indexing; in this case, the citations to the year prior to volume 1, and the number of articles published in the year prior to volume 1, are known zero values.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Journals that are indexed starting with a volume other than the first volume will not get an impact factor until they have been indexed for three years.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Occasionally, *Journal Citation Reports* assigns an impact factor to new journals with less than two years of indexing, based on partial citation data.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The calculation always uses two complete and known years of item counts, but for new titles one of the known counts is zero.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Annuals and other irregular publications sometimes publish no items in a particular year, affecting the count.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The impact factor relates to a specific time period; it is possible to calculate it for any desired period.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] For example, the JCR also includes a **five-year impact factor**, which is calculated by dividing the number of citations to the journal in a given year by the number of articles published in that journal in the previous five years.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] While originally invented as a tool to help university librarians to decide which journals to purchase, the impact factor soon became used as a measure for judging academic success.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] As impact factors are a journal-level metric, rather than an article- or individual-level metric, this use is controversial.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Eugene Garfield, the inventor of the JIF agreed with Hoeffel, but warned about the "misuse in evaluating individuals" because there is "a wide variation [of citations] from article to article within a single journal".
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Despite this warning, the use of the JIF has evolved, playing a key role in the process of assessing individual researchers, their job applications and their funding proposals.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] More targeted research has begun to provide firm evidence of how deeply the impact factor is embedded within formal and informal research assessment processes.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] A review in 2019 studied how often the JIF featured in documents related to the review, promotion, and tenure of scientists in US and Canadian universities.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] It concluded that 40% of universities focused on academic research specifically mentioned the JIF as part of such review, promotion, and tenure processes.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Numerous critiques have been made regarding the use of impact factors, both in terms of their statistical validity and also of their implications for how science is carried out and assessed.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] A 2007 study noted that the most fundamental flaw is that impact factors present the mean of data that are not normally distributed, and suggested that it would be more appropriate to present the median of these data.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] There is also a more general debate on the validity of the impact factor as a measure of journal importance and the effect of policies that editors may adopt to boost their impact factor (perhaps to the detriment of readers and writers).
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Other criticism focuses on the effect of the impact factor on the behavior of scholars, editors and other stakeholders.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Criticism of impact factors also extends to its impact on researcher behavior.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] While the emphasis on high-impact journals may lead to strategic publishing practices that prioritize journal prestige over the quality and relevance of research, it's important to acknowledge the "privilege paradox".
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Younger researchers, particularly those from under-represented regions, often lack the established reputation or networks to secure recognition outside of these metrics.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] This can lead to a narrow focus on publishing in top-tier journals, potentially compromising the diversity of research topics and methodologies.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Further criticisms argue that emphasis on impact factor results from the negative influence of neoliberal politics on academia.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Some of these arguments demand not just replacement of the impact factor with more sophisticated metrics but also discussion on the social value of research assessment and the growing precariousness of scientific careers in higher education.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] It has been stated that impact factors in particular and citation analysis in general are affected by field-dependent factors which invalidate comparisons not only across disciplines but even within different fields of research of one discipline.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The percentage of total citations occurring in the first two years after publication also varies highly among disciplines from 1–3% in the mathematical and physical sciences to 5–8% in the biological sciences.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Thus impact factors cannot be used to compare journals across disciplines.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Impact factors are sometimes used to evaluate not only the journals but the papers therein, thereby devaluing papers in certain subjects.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Other studies have repeatedly stated that impact factor is a metric for journals and should not be used to assess individual researchers or institutions.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Because impact factor is commonly accepted as a proxy for research quality, some journals adopt editorial policies and practices, some acceptable and some of dubious purpose, to increase their impact factor.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] For example, journals may publish a larger percentage of review articles which generally are cited more than research reports.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Research undertaken in 2020 on dentistry journals concluded that the publication of "systematic reviews have significant effect on the Journal Impact Factor ... while papers publishing clinical trials bear no influence on this factor.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] As a result of negotiations over whether items are "citable", impact factor variations of more than 300% have been observed.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Items considered to be uncitable—and thus are not incorporated in impact factor calculations—can, if cited, still enter into the numerator part of the equation despite the ease with which such citations could be excluded.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] This effect is hard to evaluate, for the distinction between editorial comment and short original articles is not always obvious.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] For example, letters to the editor may be part of either class.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Another less insidious tactic journals employ is to publish a large portion of its papers, or at least the papers expected to be highly cited, early in the calendar year.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] This gives those papers more time to gather citations.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Several methods, not necessarily with nefarious intent, exist for a journal to cite articles in the same journal which will increase the journal's impact factor.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Beyond editorial policies that may skew the impact factor, journals can take overt steps to game the system.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] For example, in 2007, the specialist journal *Folia Phoniatrica et Logopaedica*, with an impact factor of 0.66, published an editorial that cited all its articles from 2005 to 2006 in a protest against the "absurd scientific situation in some countries" related to use of the impact factor.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The large number of citations meant that the impact factor for that journal increased to 1.44.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] As a result of the increase, the journal was not included in the 2008 and 2009 *Journal Citation Reports*.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Coercive citation is a practice in which an editor forces an author to add extraneous citations to an article before the journal will agree to publish it, in order to inflate the journal's impact factor.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] A survey published in 2012 indicates that coercive citation has been experienced by one in five researchers working in economics, sociology, psychology, and multiple business disciplines, and it is more common in business and in journals with a lower impact factor.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Editors of leading business journals banded together to disavow the practice.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] However, cases of coercive citation have occasionally been reported for other disciplines.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The journal impact factor was originally designed by Eugene Garfield as a metric to help librarians make decisions about which journals were worth indexing, as the JIF aggregates the number of citations to articles published in each journal.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Since then, the JIF has become associated as a mark of journal "quality", and gained widespread use for evaluation of research and researchers instead, even at the institutional level.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] It thus has significant impact on steering research practices and behaviors.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] By 2010, national and international research funding institutions were already starting to point out that numerical indicators such as the JIF should not be considered as a measure of quality.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] In fact, research was indicating that the JIF is a highly manipulated metric, and the justification for its continued widespread use beyond its original narrow purpose seems due to its simplicity (easily calculable and comparable number), rather than any actual relationship to research quality.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Empirical evidence shows that the misuse of the JIF—and journal ranking metrics in general—has a number of negative consequences for the scholarly communication system.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] These include gaps between the reach of a journal and the quality of its individual papers and insufficient coverage of social sciences and humanities as well as research outputs from across Latin America, Africa, and South-East Asia.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Additional drawbacks include the marginalization of research in vernacular languages and on locally relevant topics and inducement to unethical authorship and citation practices.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] More generally, the impact factor fosters a reputation economy, where scientific success is based on publishing in prestigious journals ahead of actual research qualities such as rigorous methods, replicability and social impact.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Using journal prestige and the JIF to cultivate a competition regime in academia has been shown to have deleterious effects on research quality.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] A number of regional and international initiatives are now providing and suggesting alternative research assessment systems, including key documents such as the Leiden Manifesto and the San Francisco Declaration on Research Assessment (DORA).
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Plan S calls for a broader adoption and implementation of such initiatives alongside fundamental changes in the scholarly communication system.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] As appropriate measures of quality for authors and research, concepts of research excellence should be remodelled around transparent workflows and accessible research results.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] JIFs are still regularly used to evaluate research in many countries, which is a problem since a number of issues remain around the opacity of the metric and the fact that it is often negotiated by publishers.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Results of an impact factor can change dramatically depending on which items are considered as "citable" and therefore included in the denominator.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] One notorious example of this occurred in 1988 when it was decided that meeting abstracts published in *FASEB Journal* would no longer be included in the denominator.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The journal's impact factor jumped from 0.24 in 1988 to 18.3 in 1989.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Publishers routinely discuss with Clarivate how to improve the "accuracy" of their journals' impact factor and therefore get higher scores.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Such discussions routinely produce "negotiated values" which result in dramatic changes in the observed scores for dozens of journals, sometimes after unrelated events like the purchase by one of the larger publishers.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Because citation counts have highly skewed distributions, the mean number of citations is potentially misleading if used to gauge the typical impact of articles in the journal rather than the overall impact of the journal itself.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] For example, about 90% of *Nature*'s 2004 impact factor was based on only a quarter of its publications.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Thus the actual number of citations for a single article in the journal is in most cases much lower than the mean number of citations across articles.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Furthermore, the strength of the relationship between impact factors of journals and the citation rates of the papers therein has been steadily decreasing since articles began to be available digitally.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] This article received more than 6,600 citations.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] As a consequence, the impact factor of the journal *Acta Crystallographica Section A* rose from 2.051 in 2008 to 49.926 in 2009, more than *Nature* (at 31.434) and *Science* (at 28.103).
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The second-most cited article in *Acta Crystallographica Section A* in 2008 had only 28 citations.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Critics of the JIF state that use of the arithmetic mean in its calculation is problematic because the pattern of citation distribution is skewed and citation distributions metrics have been proposed as an alternative to impact factors.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] However, there have also been pleas to take a more nuanced approach to judging the distribution skewness of the impact factor.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] While the underlying mathematical model is publicly known, the dataset which is used to calculate the JIF is not publicly available.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] This prompted criticism: "Just as scientists would not accept the findings in a scientific paper without seeing the primary data, so should they not rely on Thomson Scientific's impact factor, which is based on hidden data".
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] However, a 2019 article demonstrated that "with access to the data and careful cleaning, the JIF can be reproduced", although this required much labour to achieve.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] It indicated that by querying open access or partly open-access databases, like Google Scholar, ResearchGate, and Scopus, it is possible to calculate approximate impact factors without the need to purchase Web of Science / JCR.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Just as the impact factor has attracted criticism for various immediate problems associated with its application, so has there also been criticism that its application undermines the broader process of science.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Research has indicated that bibliometrics figures, particularly the impact factor, decrease the quality of peer review an article receives, cause a reluctance to share data, decrease the quality of articles, and a reduce the scope of publishable research.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Given the growing criticism and its widespread usage as a means of research assessment, organisations and institutions have begun to take steps to move away from the journal impact factor.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The UK's Research Assessment Exercise for 2014 also banned the journal impact factor although evidence suggested that this ban was often ignored.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Publishers, even those with high impact factors, also recognised the flaws.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] In 2021, Utrecht University promised to abandon all quantitative bibliometrics, including the impact factor.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The university stated that "it has become a very sick model that goes beyond what is really relevant for science and putting science forward".
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] This followed a 2018 decision by the main Dutch funding body for research, NWO, to remove all references to journal impact factors and the h-index in all call texts and application forms.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Utrecht's decision met with some resistance.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] An open letter signed by over 150 Dutch academics argued that, while imperfect, the JIF is still useful, and that omitting it "will lead to randomness and a compromising of scientific quality".
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] A given journal may attain a different quartile or percentile in different categories.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] As with the impact factor, there are some nuances to this: for example, Clarivate excludes certain article types (such as news items, correspondence, and errata) from the denominator.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Additional journal-level metrics are available from other organizations.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] For example, *CiteScore* is a metric for serial titles in Scopus launched in December 2016 by Elsevier.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] While these metrics apply only to journals, there are also author-level metrics, such as the h-index, that apply to individual researchers.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] In addition, article-level metrics measure impact at an article level instead of journal level.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Other more general alternative metrics, or "altmetrics", that include article views, downloads, or mentions in social media, offer a different perspective on research impact, concentrating more on immediate social impact in and outside academia.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Fake impact factors or bogus impact factors are produced by certain companies or individuals.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] According to an article published in the *Electronic Physician*, these include Global Impact Factor, Citefactor, and Universal Impact Factor.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Jeffrey Beall maintained a list of such misleading metrics.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Another deceitful practice is reporting "alternative impact factors", calculated as the average number of citations per article using citation indices other than JCR such as Google Scholar (e.g., "Google-based Journal Impact Factor") or Microsoft Academic.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] False impact factors are often used by predatory publishers.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] Consulting Journal Citation Reports' master journal list can confirm if a publication is indexed by the *Journal Citation Reports*.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/impact-factor] The use of fake impact metrics is considered a red flag.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] It was initially published in 1972 (ISO 4:1972), with a second edition published in 1984 (ISO 4:1984), and the third edition in 1997 (ISO 4:1997).
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) has appointed the ISSN International Centre as the registration authority for ISO 4.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] It maintains the **List of Title Word Abbreviations** (LTWA), which contains standard abbreviations for words commonly found in serial titles.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] The most recent LTWA was updated on 26 February 2024.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] As of April 2026, it includes over 37,000 abbreviations across more than 60 languages.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] One provision of ISO 4 is that components of compound words should be abbreviated.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] For hyphenated terms, each part is treated as a standalone word; for example, *African-American* becomes *Afr.Am.*, typically with periods and no spaces between components.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] A major use of ISO 4 is to abbreviate the names of scientific journals using the LTWA.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] For instance, under ISO 4 standards, the *Journal of Biological Chemistry* is cited as *J.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] Chem.*, and the *Journal of Polymer Science Part A* should be cited as *J.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] A* (capitalization is not specified by the standard).
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] The standard notes that "Full stops shall only be used to indicate an abbreviation.
[src:applied-mechanics-reviews/iso-4-infobox] Full stops may be omitted from abbreviated words in applications that require limited use of punctuation" (section 4.6).
